<typeStatus box="[151,204,1978,2001]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Gorham, 1892 Gorham 1892: 733" authorityName="Gorham, 1892 Gorham" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mouhoti">
<emphasis box="[301,523,1978,2001]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Xenorthrius mouhoti</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gorham, H. S." pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="718 - 746" refId="ref52337" refString="Gorham, H. S. (1892) Viaggio di Leonardo Fea in Birmania e Vicine. Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova, Ser. 2 a 12 (32), 718 - 746." type="journal article" year="1892">Gorham, 1892 Gorham 1892: 733</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorham, H. S." box="[413,524,2010,2033]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="566 - 581" refId="ref52378" refString="Gorham, H. S. (1893) A list of the Coleoptera, of the family Cleridae, collected by Mr. Doherty in Burmah and Northern India, with descriptions of new species; and of some species from Borneo, Perak, &amp; c., from the collection of Alexander Fry, Esq. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 39, 566 - 581." type="journal article" year="1893">1893: 575</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Schenkling, S." box="[535,810,2010,2033]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 124" refId="ref53007" refString="Schenkling, S. (1903 a) Coleoptera. Malacodermata. Fam. Cleridae. Genera Insectorum, 13 Fascicule. P. Wytsman, Bruxelles, Belgium, 1 - 124." type="book chapter" year="1903">Schenkling 1903a: 46–47</bibRefCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,230,151,177]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Head:</emphasis>
Punctation setiferous, interstices among punctures shiny; labrum bilobed, anterior margin densely vested with short setae, remainder laterally vested with longer setae; anterior part of clypeus semi-transparent, smooth, anterior margin of posterior part of clypeus mostly concave, posterior margin mostly convex; distal part of clypeus trapezoidal, proximal part usually darker than anterior part; terminal maxillary palpomeres digitiform, darker than other segments; terminal labial palpomeres securiform (
<figureCitation box="[1107,1179,301,327]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="7.[151,255,1313,1337]" captionTargetBox="[161,1431,642,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-301@7.[151,1436,642,1292]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 1. Xenorthrius umbratus: Lower surface of head and pronotum with mouthparts." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); mandibles laterally vested with long setae; eyes coarsely facetted, protruding laterally, margined, emarginate at antennal insertion, with sparse pubescence between ommatidia; interocular space larger than one eye width (as viewed from above); genae behind the eyes with distinct wrinkles; gula smooth, gular process interspecifically varying in width (
<figureCitation box="[233,304,450,476]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,255,1754,1778]" captionTargetBox="[373,1213,1411,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-303@7.[373,1213,1401,1733]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gular process: (A) Xenorthrius penangis and (B) Xenorthrius umbratus." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); antennae with 11 antennomeres, filiform (
<figureCitation box="[814,982,450,476]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,256,678,702]" captionTargetBox="[216,1369,426,639]" captionTargetId="figure-243@8.[216,1371,426,656]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Antennae: (A) Xenorthrius doliaris, (B) Xenorthrius abruptepunctatus, (C) Xenorthrius simplex and (D) Xenorthrius berndi." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3A and C</figureCitation>
), length interspecifically variable (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,256,678,702]" captionTargetBox="[216,1369,426,639]" captionTargetId="figure-243@8.[216,1371,426,656]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Antennae: (A) Xenorthrius doliaris, (B) Xenorthrius abruptepunctatus, (C) Xenorthrius simplex and (D) Xenorthrius berndi." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) and sometimes sexually dimorphic (longer in males), scape bent, flattened towards the eyes, A1 longer than A2, A2 shorter than A3, terminal three antennomeres forming a club (
<figureCitation box="[975,1067,525,551]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,256,678,702]" captionTargetBox="[216,1369,426,639]" captionTargetId="figure-243@8.[216,1371,426,656]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Antennae: (A) Xenorthrius doliaris, (B) Xenorthrius abruptepunctatus, (C) Xenorthrius simplex and (D) Xenorthrius berndi." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
), A11 elongate in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[1284,1435,525,550]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stefanieae">
<emphasis box="[1284,1435,525,550]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">X. stefanieae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[200,309,562,587]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berndi">
<emphasis box="[200,309,562,587]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">X. berndi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[325,418,562,588]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,256,678,702]" captionTargetBox="[216,1369,426,639]" captionTargetId="figure-243@8.[216,1371,426,656]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Antennae: (A) Xenorthrius doliaris, (B) Xenorthrius abruptepunctatus, (C) Xenorthrius simplex and (D) Xenorthrius berndi." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
), antennomeres vested with short setae, club tomented yellowish to white.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1119,1313,1337]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" startId="7.[151,255,1313,1337]" targetBox="[161,1431,642,1292]" targetPageId="7">
