<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1818,2031]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,152,364]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,300,1818,1844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Thorax:</emphasis>
Punctation setiferous, interstices among punctures shiny; pronotum longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[1334,1427,1818,1844]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1112,1136]" captionTargetBox="[257,1329,792,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-247@8.[226,1360,792,1090]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pronota: (A) Xenorthrius truncatus, (B) Xenorthrius ephippiatus and (C) Xenorthrius decoratus." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
) or subquadrate (
<figureCitation box="[356,455,1856,1882]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1112,1136]" captionTargetBox="[257,1329,792,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-247@8.[226,1360,792,1090]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pronota: (A) Xenorthrius truncatus, (B) Xenorthrius ephippiatus and (C) Xenorthrius decoratus." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
), sides slightly to distinctly convex between anterior and posterior transverse depressions (
<figureCitation box="[312,410,1893,1919]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1112,1136]" captionTargetBox="[257,1329,792,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-247@8.[226,1360,792,1090]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Pronota: (A) Xenorthrius truncatus, (B) Xenorthrius ephippiatus and (C) Xenorthrius decoratus." pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
); each side of pronotum with a dorsolateral fovea; subapical transverse depression slightly impressed; prebasal transverse depression distinct; punctation mostly coarser on pronotum proper; pronotal arch broadest centrally; collar broadened laterally; prosternum smooth, sometimes with microsculpture, not pilose except for a line of setae at the anterior margin, pro-intercoxal process narrow, often dilated distally (
<figureCitation box="[428,502,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="7.[151,255,1313,1337]" captionTargetBox="[161,1431,642,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-301@7.[151,1436,642,1292]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 1. Xenorthrius umbratus: Lower surface of head and pronotum with mouthparts." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); procoxal cavities wide open behind; mesosternum coarsely punctured to wrinkled, anterior mesosternal process distinct, narrow, with a subtriangular sulcus in the middle, intercoxal mesosternal process projecting ventrally; ventral part of mesepisternum smooth (except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[1220,1350,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cruralis">
<emphasis box="[1220,1350,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">X. cruralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Schenkling" baseAuthorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">X. tuberculicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with isolated, often large punctation, dorsal part coarsely punctured; punctation of metasternum fine, discriminal line smooth; metendosternite (
<figureCitation box="[892,965,301,327]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1711,1735]" captionText="FIGURE 5. Metendosternite: Xenorthrius loricus." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) not significantly varying, furcal arms broad, apically dilated, laminae well developed.
</paragraph>
