<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1785,2036]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1436,152,364]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,287,1785,1811]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Elytra:</emphasis>
Elytral base without abrupt margin, lateral margins subparallel, elytra broadest behind middle, apices rounded (most species), strongly dehiscent (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Schenkling" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[770,949,1824,1849]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prolongatus">
<emphasis box="[770,949,1824,1849]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">X. prolongatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[1009,1134,1824,1849]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcalis">
<emphasis box="[1009,1134,1824,1849]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">X. furcalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)(
<figureCitation box="[1152,1248,1823,1849]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,258,850,874]" captionTargetBox="[227,1360,415,829]" captionTargetId="figure-170@9.[227,1360,415,829]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Elytral apices: (A) dentate (Xenorthrius truncatus), (B) dehiscent (Xenorthrius prolongatus) and (C) rounded (Xenorthrius geniculatus)." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
), or dentate (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorham" authorityYear="1893" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">X. truncatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[325,474,1861,1886]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scordalus">
<emphasis box="[325,474,1861,1886]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">X. scordalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)(
<figureCitation box="[493,592,1861,1887]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,258,850,874]" captionTargetBox="[227,1360,415,829]" captionTargetId="figure-170@9.[227,1360,415,829]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Elytral apices: (A) dentate (Xenorthrius truncatus), (B) dehiscent (Xenorthrius prolongatus) and (C) rounded (Xenorthrius geniculatus)." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
); setae arising from between striae and among punctation, punctation asetiferous, often more distinct in basal half and in darker areas, in most species punctation in basal half of elytra rasp-like (meaning the interstices among punctation bulging over the punctures, see 
<figureCitation box="[1218,1288,1935,1961]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,255,1403,1427]" captionTargetBox="[532,1029,989,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-173@9.[532,1029,989,1381]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Xenorthrius scordalus: rasp-like punctation in basal half of elytra." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
), punctation often obsolete in the middle of elytron near suture; subcutaneous structures of elytra mostly visible through lighter areas (this often makes punctures appear larger than their actual size); elytral punctation arranged into ten striae, in some species additional punctures are present between the striae, one species with more or less irregular punctation (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gerstmeier &amp; Eberle" authorityYear="2010" box="[399,518,189,214]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Xenorthrius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="temeris">
<emphasis box="[399,518,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">X. temeris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), in most of the species the interstices in the apical half of elytra are carinated; hindwing (
<figureCitation box="[278,348,226,252]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,255,1973,1997]" captionTargetBox="[228,1359,1500,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-176@9.[228,1359,1500,1952]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Xenorthrius loricus: Wing venation. AA = anal anterior, CuA = cubitus anterior, MP = media posterior, Rc = radial cell, Sc = subcosta." pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) with wedge cell open, anal anterior 1+2 very small or absent, margin of radial cell strongly sclerotized, the highest interspecific variability occurs in anterior cubital veins and posterior medial veins 3 and 4 where some proportions slightly differ, in some specimens cubitus anterior 1 is very short or even obsolete.
</paragraph>
